Anku on Ghana Economy
By since Anku
This week I am dealing with
Ghana’s economic policy which
is alleged by some pseudo-excel-ts to be communities, Next
Week We shall examine Ghana's
foreign policy.
There are five sectors in
Ghana's economy: " 1) In the
state’s sector enterprises are
entirely state-owned. This includes such industries as a soap
factory and a june bag factory.
The railways and airfare are
government owned. in addition
to the food produced by small
private farmers, the government produces food on 105 state
farms using modern lauderdale. technological methods.
Four of these are run by soviet experts and three, by iso‘all. The lesbians and Israelis are not to be the only foreignr
era to help implement Ghana’s
agricultural revolution—a revolution which is supposed to take
place on the individual farms
as much as on state farms or
corporations. The U. S. recently sent over 250 tons oi agricultural supplies, under the U. 5.
technical assistance program,
to be used at ﬁve new training
centers for farmers,
2) The joint State - private
sector is managed by an agree-
ment between the government
and private investors of copy ‘
tax. Ghana's biggest single in- ‘
district project is the $197 million delta hydroelectric project, The new dam is being changed on a littyeiiity basis by
Ghania‘and following sources:
the World Bank, the United '
States and Britain.
